    <h2>Section 2: Convection Oven Maintenance</h2>

    <p>Convection ovens have more moving parts than deck ovens — primarily the fan system. The fan motor, fan wheel, and associated bearings are the critical wear components. Most convection oven failures in India trace back to either neglected fan systems or scale build-up in models with steam injection.</p>

    <h3>Daily Maintenance — Convection Oven</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Clean interior after last use:</strong> While the oven is still warm (not hot), wipe down interior walls, ceiling, and floor with a damp cloth. Remove any food residue or drips. Sugar and fat residue that carbonises is difficult to remove and absorbs odours that contaminate subsequent batches.</li>
      <li><strong>Clean door glass:</strong> Wipe interior and exterior door glass clean. Grease film on the interior glass bakes into a darkening layer that blocks visibility and is progressively harder to remove. A clean door glass also allows you to monitor baking progress without opening the door (which disrupts temperature and humidity).</li>
      <li><strong>Check fan operation:</strong> Listen to the fan at start-up and during operation. A healthy convection fan is quiet and smooth. Grinding, scraping, or irregular sounds indicate bearing wear, an unbalanced fan wheel, or debris in the fan housing. Address immediately — a seized fan motor in peak production is a half-day shutdown.</li>
      <li><strong>Empty and clean drip tray:</strong> The drip tray or grease collector at the oven base collects drips from baking. Empty and wipe clean daily to prevent smoke, odour, and fire risk from accumulated grease.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Weekly Maintenance — Convection Oven</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Deep clean with oven cleaner:</strong> Apply a commercial oven degreaser (diluted per instructions) to interior surfaces. Allow to dwell, then scrub with a non-scratch pad and rinse thoroughly. Never use abrasive scourers on stainless interiors — they create micro-scratches that harbour bacteria and accelerate corrosion.</li>
      <li><strong>Remove and clean fan cover/baffle:</strong> Most convection ovens have a removable rear baffle or panel covering the fan. Remove it weekly, wash in hot soapy water, and inspect the fan wheel for grease build-up. A grease-coated fan wheel is out of balance — it generates vibration, accelerates bearing wear, and reduces airflow efficiency.</li>
      <li><strong>Inspect door seal:</strong> The door seal on a convection oven takes more wear than a deck oven seal because the door is opened far more frequently during a shift. Check for cracks, compression fatigue (the seal no longer springs back when pressed), and loose sections. Replace at the first sign of failure.</li>
      <li><strong>Check tray runners and guides:</strong> Inspect tray runners for straightness and lubrication. Bent runners cause trays to stick, which leads to operators forcing trays and bending the runners further. Clean and apply a food-safe lubricant to runner tracks monthly.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Monthly Maintenance — Convection Oven</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Fan motor inspection:</strong> With the oven off and cool, manually rotate the fan wheel. It should spin freely with no resistance, grinding, or side-play in the shaft. Any roughness indicates bearing wear. Convection oven fan motor bearings typically last 3–5 years with regular cleaning and are cheap to replace (₹500–₹2,500 for bearings). Ignored, they seize and take the motor with them (₹4,000–₹15,000 for a replacement motor).</li>
      <li><strong>Thermostat and probe calibration:</strong> Use the same calibration method as deck ovens — compare a calibrated thermometer against the display at a known setpoint. Convection oven temperature probes drift over time, especially in high-humidity environments (steam injection models). More than ±8°C variance indicates the probe needs replacement or recalibration.</li>
      <li><strong>Heating element inspection:</strong> With the oven cold and isolated from mains power, visually inspect all heating elements. Check for breaks, bowing (element has sagged from heat cycling), or discolouration. A multimeter check of element resistance by a qualified technician is the most reliable test — an element showing resistance outside specification should be replaced proactively.</li>
      <li><strong>Descale steam system (if equipped):</strong> Same approach as deck ovens. Indian water hardness makes this a monthly necessity in most cities. Delhi, Bengaluru, Hyderabad, and Ahmedabad are particularly hard-water cities — in these locations, weekly descaling of steam components may be necessary.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Section 3: Rotary Rack Oven Maintenance</h2>

    <p>Rotary rack ovens are the most mechanically complex bakery ovens — and the most expensive to repair when neglected. The rotating rack mechanism, burner system (most are gas-fired in India), air circulation system, and steam generator all require attention. A rotary rack oven in poor condition can cost ₹1,50,000–₹5,00,000 in repairs that a systematic maintenance programme would have prevented entirely.</p>

    <h3>Daily Maintenance — Rotary Rack Oven</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Clean oven floor and walls after last use:</strong> Rotary rack ovens accumulate crumbs and grease on the oven floor rapidly. Clean the floor while still warm. Use a long-handled brush or scraper — the oven cavity is deep and hot.</li>
      <li><strong>Inspect rotation mechanism:</strong> Watch the rack rotate during the first load of the day. Rotation should be smooth, consistent, and without wobble or scraping sounds. Any irregular motion should be investigated before further use — a falling rack under load is extremely dangerous.</li>
      <li><strong>Check rack and hanger:</strong> Inspect the rack suspension hook or drive arm for visible deformation or wear. Racks loaded with 200–400 kg of product exert significant stress on suspension components.</li>
      <li><strong>Burner ignition check (gas ovens):</strong> Verify clean, stable ignition at start-up. A burner that takes multiple ignition attempts indicates a dirty igniter electrode, faulty igniter transformer, or gas pressure issue.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Weekly Maintenance — Rotary Rack Oven</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Clean heat exchanger or burner tubes:</strong> Carbon and grease accumulation on burner tubes or heat exchanger surfaces reduces heat transfer efficiency — the oven uses more gas to reach temperature. Brush clean weekly with a stiff wire brush designed for the purpose.</li>
      <li><strong>Inspect drive chain or belt (rotation mechanism):</strong> Check drive chain tension, lubrication, and for any wear or link elongation. Apply food-safe chain lubricant weekly. A worn chain is cheap to replace (₹1,500–₹5,000). A chain that snaps mid-rotation drops the loaded rack onto the oven floor — extremely expensive damage.</li>
      <li><strong>Clean steam generator and check water level:</strong> Rotary rack oven steam generators operate at higher pressure than deck oven steam systems. Clean the steam generator tank and inspect the water level sensor weekly. A dry-running steam generator fails quickly and expensively.</li>
      <li><strong>Check door seals and latches:</strong> Rotary rack oven doors are large and heavy. Inspect the full perimeter seal and all latching points. A door that doesn't seal completely causes large temperature losses and uneven baking.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Monthly Maintenance — Rotary Rack Oven</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Full rotation mechanism service:</strong> Inspect all bearings in the rotation drive system. Check the motor, gearbox oil level (if applicable), drive shaft, and mounting brackets. Lubricate all grease points per the manufacturer's schedule. This is the most critical monthly task for rotary rack ovens — bearing or gearbox failure is the most expensive and time-consuming repair.</li>
      <li><strong>Burner and combustion analysis:</strong> Have a gas technician check burner combustion monthly. A CO₂ / O₂ analysis of flue gases tells you if the air-to-gas ratio is correct. A rich mixture wastes gas and produces soot; a lean mixture overheats components. In India, gas pressure fluctuations from PNG or LPG supplies make this analysis particularly important.</li>
      <li><strong>Full descale of steam system:</strong> The high-capacity steam generator in a rotary rack oven accumulates scale faster than smaller systems. Perform a full descale cycle or manual descale procedure monthly. Failure to descale is the most common cause of steam system failure in Indian rotary rack ovens.</li>
      <li><strong>Control system inspection:</strong> Check all temperature sensors, pressure switches, and safety interlocks. The high-limit thermostat (which shuts the oven down if temperature exceeds safe limits) is a critical safety device — verify it's functioning correctly by checking its calibration against a reference thermometer.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Section 4: Common Problems and DIY Fixes</h2>

    <h3>Problem: Uneven Baking (Hot Spots)</h3>
    <p><strong>Likely causes:</strong> dirty or blocked heating elements, failed heating element section, fan wheel imbalance (convection), calibration drift between deck thermostat zones (deck oven), rotation mechanism slowing (rotary rack).</p>
    <p><strong>DIY check:</strong> Place a tray of bread rolls or biscuits in the oven and bake to the point where colour difference is visible. Note where the over-browned and under-browned areas are. For a convection oven, uneven browning from front-to-back suggests a partially failed element or fan issue. For a deck oven, zone-specific hot spots typically indicate a specific heating element section.</p>
    <p><strong>Fix:</strong> Clean all elements and run a thermostat calibration check first — most "hot spot" problems in Indian bakeries are dirty elements or thermostat drift, both of which are free to fix. If cleaning and calibration don't resolve it, call a technician for element resistance testing.</p>

    <h3>Problem: Oven Not Reaching Set Temperature</h3>
    <p><strong>Likely causes:</strong> failed heating element, faulty temperature probe/thermostat, failed contactor or relay (electric ovens), gas pressure issue or blocked burner (gas ovens), failed door seal causing excessive heat loss.</p>
    <p><strong>DIY check:</strong> First check the door seal — it's the most commonly overlooked cause. Then check if the oven heats slowly but reaches temperature (probe drift) or genuinely never reaches temperature (element or burner failure).</p>
    <p><strong>Fix:</strong> Replace door seal if damaged (DIY-able, ₹500–₹3,000 in parts). Probe replacement is a straightforward technician job (₹1,500–₹5,000 including labour). Element replacement requires isolating mains power and should be done by a qualified electrician or oven technician.</p>

    <h3>Problem: Door Won't Close / Seal Properly</h3>
    <p><strong>Likely causes:</strong> worn gasket, bent door hinge, accumulated food debris in door channel, spring tension loss.</p>
    <p><strong>DIY fix:</strong> Clean the door channel and gasket seat thoroughly — baked-on debris is a very common cause. If the gasket is worn, replace it (this is a DIY job for most oven models — the gasket typically clips or slides into a channel). If the door frame itself is bent (common in ovens that have been loaded with heavy trays dropped in hard), a technician with straightening tools is required.</p>

    <h3>Problem: Steam Not Working</h3>
    <p><strong>Likely causes:</strong> blocked injector nozzles (scale), failed steam generator element, low water supply to generator, failed solenoid valve, failed water level sensor.</p>
    <p><strong>DIY fix:</strong> Descale the steam system completely before calling a technician — in India's hard water environment, scale blockage is the cause of 70–80% of steam failures. If descaling doesn't restore steam, check water supply (adequate pressure and flow to the generator), then check the solenoid valve (a clicking sound when steam is commanded but no steam produced often indicates the solenoid is operating but the valve itself is stuck — scale again).</p>

    <h3>Problem: Thermostat Shows Wrong Temperature</h3>
    <p><strong>Likely causes:</strong> temperature probe drift (most common), faulty thermostat controller, probe physically damaged or poorly positioned.</p>
    <p><strong>DIY calibration:</strong> Use a calibrated oven thermometer to establish actual temperature at a known setpoint. If the variance is consistent (e.g., always reads 20°C high), check if your oven thermostat has a calibration offset setting in the service menu — many commercial ovens allow a digital offset correction without replacing the probe. If variance is inconsistent or erratic, the probe needs replacement.</p>

    <h3>Problem: Oven Tripping the Electrical Circuit</h3>
    <p><strong>Likely causes:</strong> degraded heating element with insulation failure causing an earth fault, short circuit in wiring, overloaded circuit (oven on a circuit not rated for its load), faulty contactor.</p>
    <p><strong>Important:</strong> Do not bypass or upsize the circuit breaker to "fix" a tripping problem. This is a safety hazard and a fire risk. Call a qualified electrician. A tripping oven is telling you there is an electrical fault that needs diagnosis — in India, many bakery fires start from exactly this kind of ignored electrical fault.</p>

