    <h2>Section 5: AMC (Annual Maintenance Contracts) — What to Look For</h2>

    <p>An Annual Maintenance Contract (AMC) with a qualified service company is, for most commercial bakeries, the most cost-effective way to keep an oven running reliably. An AMC shifts the burden of scheduling maintenance from the bakery owner to the service provider, ensures genuine parts are used, and typically reduces unplanned breakdown costs significantly.</p>

    <h3>What a Good AMC Should Include</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Scheduled preventive maintenance visits:</strong> A minimum of 2 visits per year (quarterly is better for high-use ovens). Each visit should include thermostat calibration, element inspection, seal inspection, cleaning, and a written service report.</li>
      <li><strong>Breakdown response time commitment:</strong> Maximum 24-hour response for call-outs, 48-hour for non-critical issues. Any AMC without a stated response time is not worth the paper it's written on.</li>
      <li><strong>Genuine OEM or approved spare parts:</strong> Insist on this in writing. Some AMC providers cut costs by fitting non-OEM parts that fail prematurely and void the original warranty.</li>
      <li><strong>Labour coverage for all repairs:</strong> A "comprehensive" AMC covers both parts and labour. A "non-comprehensive" (CAMC vs AMC in India) covers labour only. Know which type you're signing — some providers sell non-comprehensive contracts as if they were comprehensive.</li>
      <li><strong>Exclusions clearly listed:</strong> What is NOT covered? Physical damage, improper use, cosmetic damage, consumables (door seals, gaskets used frequently) — these are standard exclusions. Ensure you understand them before signing.</li>
      <li><strong>Service report documentation:</strong> Each visit should produce a signed service report that forms part of your maintenance record. This is required for warranty claims and is good practice for FSSAI inspections.</li>
    </ul>

